205
00:16:53,455 --> 00:17:00,341
[SPEAKER_05]: And they're going to be sharing sustainable tips that we give them over the loudspeaker at different points during the game.

206
00:17:00,381 --> 00:17:01,662
[SPEAKER_05]: So it sounds like it'll be fun.

207
00:17:02,823 --> 00:17:03,204
[SPEAKER_05]: OK.

208
00:17:08,869 --> 00:17:15,054
[SPEAKER_05]: And let me drop, again, let me drop into the chat the link for that as well.

209
00:17:19,062 --> 00:17:20,443
[SPEAKER_09]: Brenda, do you know what time?

210
00:17:20,463 --> 00:17:30,788
[SPEAKER_09]: I know what time it starts, but I don't know if they're going to do it during the day or have the energy fest during the game, which is at six.

211
00:17:31,809 --> 00:17:32,249
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you know?

212
00:17:32,269 --> 00:17:35,851
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it's during the game, yeah.

213
00:17:36,832 --> 00:17:42,215
[SPEAKER_05]: Bob's going to be doing the wind turbine tours ahead of time at six o'clock.

214
00:17:43,112 --> 00:17:49,857
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think the idea with the energy fest is like, as people are coming into the game, they can stop at the tables and stuff like that.

215
00:17:50,097 --> 00:17:57,283
[SPEAKER_05]: And, uh, I think the, the tours are probably going to be more for the, uh, the team members who are really excited about it.

216
00:17:58,484 --> 00:17:58,844
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

217
00:18:00,806 --> 00:18:06,931
[SPEAKER_11]: And I don't know if you, I missed it, if you mentioned it, but there's going to be the just hummus food truck there, apparently.

218
00:18:07,311 --> 00:18:08,011
[SPEAKER_11]: Right.

219
00:18:08,072 --> 00:18:08,632
[SPEAKER_11]: Nice too.

220
00:18:09,333 --> 00:18:09,533
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes.

221
00:18:18,187 --> 00:18:29,275
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, moving on, um, for the, um, electric aggregation program, our supply contract for that expires at the end of the year.

222
00:18:29,295 --> 00:18:38,321
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, we're probably going to go out to bid for that this spring in the April-May time frame.

223
00:18:39,582 --> 00:18:45,327
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, and I think this time around, we're probably going to increase the renewable energy content.

224
00:18:47,048 --> 00:18:52,993
[SPEAKER_05]: Many communities right now are at 10%, we're at five of additional renewable content.

225
00:18:54,114 --> 00:19:02,561
[SPEAKER_05]: Some of those actually at 20% for their default service that everyone is automatically opted into.

226
00:19:04,302 --> 00:19:11,789
[SPEAKER_05]: So obviously we need to balance cost and the renewable content, but I think our goal this time around is to be at least at 10% additional content.

227
00:19:19,376 --> 00:19:36,030
[SPEAKER_11]: May I ask just on that front, so we were able to benefit from aggregation locked in pricing when national grids utility rates spiked.

228
00:19:38,640 --> 00:19:41,481
[SPEAKER_11]: And we knew it in advance, which was great.

229
00:19:42,121 --> 00:19:51,545
[SPEAKER_11]: So I just wanted to know, when roughly do we get a sense of what the likely option rates are?

230
00:19:52,725 --> 00:19:57,667
[SPEAKER_11]: How far in advance would we start to know that?

231
00:19:57,687 --> 00:19:58,027
[SPEAKER_11]: Do you know?

232
00:19:59,752 --> 00:20:01,833
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't remember exactly when.

233
00:20:01,853 --> 00:20:10,714
[SPEAKER_05]: I know that we won't know what the fall-winter switch will be when we go out to bid this spring.

234
00:20:12,255 --> 00:20:21,797
[SPEAKER_05]: We're doing that a little bit blind, so we'll be locking in those prices in the spring, but obviously, we'll keep an eye on it.

235
00:20:22,057 --> 00:20:27,758
[SPEAKER_05]: As we get closer to it, the prices are significantly lower than what we're doing, then we'll rethink this.

236
00:20:29,578 --> 00:20:31,640
[SPEAKER_05]: It seems unlikely, they usually go up in the winter.

237
00:20:32,280 --> 00:20:32,460
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

238
00:20:33,221 --> 00:20:33,421
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

239
00:20:33,821 --> 00:20:34,021
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

240
00:20:35,883 --> 00:20:39,465
[SPEAKER_08]: Quick question on the renewable portion of that as well.

241
00:20:39,925 --> 00:20:48,872
[SPEAKER_08]: The 5 or 10 percent, are there any restrictions on what kind of resource that needs to come from or where those resources need to be located?

242
00:20:48,892 --> 00:20:50,813
[SPEAKER_08]: Do they need to be within Massachusetts?

243
00:20:51,453 --> 00:20:55,036
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm interested in a little more information on that if you have it.

244
00:20:55,881 --> 00:21:02,305
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, so they need to be MAS class 1 RECs, which doesn't limit it to Massachusetts.

245
00:21:02,345 --> 00:21:06,807
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it limits it to the ISO New England area.

246
00:21:08,448 --> 00:21:11,650
[SPEAKER_05]: But they're class 1 RECs.

247
00:21:11,690 --> 00:21:19,315
[SPEAKER_05]: They're non-emitting renewable content.

248
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:24,678
[SPEAKER_05]: And I can share more information about that if you are interested.

249
00:21:25,814 --> 00:21:26,654
[SPEAKER_08]: No, that's okay.

250
00:21:26,754 --> 00:21:26,954
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks.

251
00:21:27,075 --> 00:21:41,861
[SPEAKER_08]: I was just wondering if we had any sort of restrictions or anything sort of above and beyond what is mandated for like a retail entity here, but that answers it.

252
00:21:42,381 --> 00:21:42,521
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks.

253
00:21:52,229 --> 00:22:04,161
[SPEAKER_05]: So moving on, we had a we held a specialized code training on the so on the stretch and specialized codes actually for building inspectors at the library on February 22.

254
00:22:07,224 --> 00:22:14,007
[SPEAKER_05]: I would did more than 40 people came from municipalities all around.

255
00:22:15,108 --> 00:22:20,151
[SPEAKER_05]: This is the first real in person training that has been held on this in the area.

256
00:22:23,252 --> 00:22:30,477
[SPEAKER_05]: I intended it to be for Medford, but we had so many inspectors asking for it that we just opened it up to everyone, and it was great.

257
00:22:31,218 --> 00:22:37,342
[SPEAKER_05]: There was a lot of conversation, and I think it made people a lot more comfortable with the material.

258
00:22:40,437 --> 00:22:46,940
[SPEAKER_05]: This one was focused on the residential code, so we'll be doing one on the commercial code for building inspectors next.

259
00:22:48,540 --> 00:22:54,822
[SPEAKER_05]: And then we'll hold some more open ones for building owners, developers, contractors, anyone who's interested.

260
00:22:57,883 --> 00:23:00,384
[SPEAKER_05]: Those aren't scheduled yet, but soon to come.

261
00:23:01,705 --> 00:23:05,366
[SPEAKER_11]: May I just ask on that front, were you present for that?

262
00:23:09,068 --> 00:23:09,188
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes.

263
00:23:09,749 --> 00:23:16,135
[SPEAKER_11]: And what did you think the inspector feeling was?

264
00:23:16,155 --> 00:23:18,397
[SPEAKER_11]: How were they feeling about all this?

265
00:23:19,879 --> 00:23:21,200
[SPEAKER_11]: Were they okay?

266
00:23:21,220 --> 00:23:22,781
[SPEAKER_11]: Are they scared?

267
00:23:22,861 --> 00:23:24,203
[SPEAKER_11]: Are they upset?

268
00:23:25,393 --> 00:23:30,419
[SPEAKER_05]: There's a lot of concern and there's a lot of misinformation.

269
00:23:31,180 --> 00:23:43,434
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think this meeting was this in person get together is really important so folks can ask questions and express these concerns in a kind of a safer space with other inspectors.

270
00:23:45,696 --> 00:23:56,140
[SPEAKER_05]: there was a lot of concern, for instance, about the specialized code and existing buildings, which the specialized code doesn't apply to existing buildings.

271
00:23:56,180 --> 00:23:57,920
[SPEAKER_05]: That's the stretch code.

272
00:23:57,960 --> 00:24:02,442
[SPEAKER_05]: And so there was a lot of kind of misunderstanding about what applies to what.

273
00:24:04,463 --> 00:24:07,764
[SPEAKER_11]: May I also just ask who was leading the training?

274
00:24:09,767 --> 00:24:16,131
[SPEAKER_05]: It's PDS Consulting, it's the consultants that MathSave hires to do this.

275
00:24:16,631 --> 00:24:21,294
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

276
00:24:21,374 --> 00:24:26,797
[SPEAKER_02]: Brenda, can I ask what the timetable is?

277
00:24:27,457 --> 00:24:35,482
[SPEAKER_02]: Is Medford adopting the more aggressive code or do we know yet?

278
00:24:37,376 --> 00:24:44,123
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, so Medford has adopted the specialized code and that takes effect July 1st.

279
00:24:44,984 --> 00:24:53,172
[SPEAKER_05]: But actually, I would say that the bigger changes are between the previous stretch code and the updated stretch code.

280
00:24:57,757 --> 00:25:07,982
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I would say mostly specialized code applies to larger multifamily buildings and things like that.

281
00:25:08,042 --> 00:25:12,043
[SPEAKER_05]: I would say the stretch code is more for smaller buildings as well.

282
00:25:19,847 --> 00:25:21,988
[SPEAKER_09]: Brenda, was this recorded?

283
00:25:24,224 --> 00:25:24,904
[SPEAKER_05]: No, it wasn't.

284
00:25:24,984 --> 00:25:30,546
[SPEAKER_05]: Although, PDS does have recordings of their webinars online.

285
00:25:31,907 --> 00:25:35,388
[SPEAKER_05]: Anybody could go online and watch their webinars anytime.

286
00:25:37,649 --> 00:25:38,789
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

287
00:25:38,809 --> 00:25:45,351
[SPEAKER_05]: They have online webinars that they do, that they have recorded and have available online, which is the same material.

288
00:25:45,371 --> 00:25:46,572
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

289
00:25:46,612 --> 00:25:47,592
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll write to you separately.

290
00:25:47,612 --> 00:25:50,073
[SPEAKER_09]: I'd like to get a link or how I find that.

291
00:25:50,633 --> 00:25:53,334
[SPEAKER_09]: I think Luke and few other members might be interested.

292
00:26:01,968 --> 00:26:04,911
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, let's see, moving on.

293
00:26:05,051 --> 00:26:15,460
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, so the Climate Equity Council had a meeting on February 26 last Monday, and Bob came to talk about the Energy and Environment Committee and how it works.

294
00:26:18,562 --> 00:26:23,184
[SPEAKER_05]: A couple of things from that meeting that I think folks here might be interested in.

295
00:26:24,345 --> 00:26:30,928
[SPEAKER_05]: Thanks to a suggestion by the Climate Equity Council, we added a translation widget to the Go Green Medford website.

296
00:26:30,948 --> 00:26:41,413
[SPEAKER_05]: The official city site has had one for a long time, but I think we didn't think to do it for the Go Green Medford one before.

297
00:26:42,374 --> 00:26:46,796
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it was great that they pointed that out and we can get that on there relatively quickly.

298
00:26:50,530 --> 00:26:57,173
[SPEAKER_05]: And then one of the things that we talked about with them was some stormwater improvements that were being planned for South Medford.

299
00:26:57,994 --> 00:27:03,597
[SPEAKER_05]: We got a grant for the design of the project, and now we're applying for a grant for the construction of it.

300
00:27:04,997 --> 00:27:18,345
[SPEAKER_05]: And the Climate Equity Council will be writing a letter of support for the grant because it's in an environmental justice neighborhood, and they recognize that that's one of the priority areas where we want to mitigate flooding.

301
00:27:19,883 --> 00:27:32,387
[SPEAKER_05]: And they'll also be helping us with outreach to neighbors in that area to educate them about the need for things like permeable surfaces, for rain barrels, things like that.

302
00:27:33,967 --> 00:27:42,350
[SPEAKER_05]: Because that neighborhood is so dense, there's not much room for green infrastructure, except in people's yards or driveways.

303
00:27:43,662 --> 00:27:54,178
[SPEAKER_05]: So while we're doing the gray infrastructure work of like increasing the size of the drains, we also want to be working with the people in the neighborhood to try to increase the green infrastructure there too.

304
00:28:04,857 --> 00:28:13,879
[SPEAKER_05]: And then I think one last thing that I wanted to mention here on the policy side of things.

305
00:28:14,839 --> 00:28:21,141
[SPEAKER_05]: So sort of a general timetable for the policy season in the State House this year.

306
00:28:21,241 --> 00:28:26,042
[SPEAKER_05]: So February, March is when a lot of the

307
00:28:26,642 --> 00:28:33,883
[SPEAKER_05]: energy bills that we're looking at would be moving to the Ways and Means Committee.

308
00:28:34,744 --> 00:28:39,064
[SPEAKER_05]: March and April is when the House will be voting on a climate bill.

309
00:28:39,945 --> 00:28:43,585
[SPEAKER_05]: April, May is when the Senate will probably be voting on a climate bill.

310
00:28:44,125 --> 00:28:48,446
[SPEAKER_05]: And then in May through July, they'd be working on a compromise bill together.

311
00:28:49,286 --> 00:28:51,327
[SPEAKER_05]: So just something to keep in mind as you're

312
00:28:52,207 --> 00:28:57,911
[SPEAKER_05]: getting information about all of the policy that folks are advocating for.

313
00:28:58,351 --> 00:28:59,892
[SPEAKER_05]: That's what the timeline is.

314
00:29:02,874 --> 00:29:16,643
[SPEAKER_05]: And then for a couple of things that I think we've talked about before, the municipal reforestation bill, that was reported favorably out by the House and the Senate Telecommunications Committee.

315
00:29:19,175 --> 00:29:27,302
[SPEAKER_05]: Telecommunications Utilities and Energy, I think it is.

316
00:29:27,322 --> 00:29:37,532
[SPEAKER_05]: I actually don't yet know if it's going to the Ways and Means Committee or next or if it's going to Reconciliation Committee, but it did get reported out favorably out of both of those.

317
00:29:39,293 --> 00:29:45,078
[SPEAKER_05]: And then the Future of Clean Heat Bill, that was reported favorably by the Senate.

318
00:29:46,245 --> 00:29:49,207
[SPEAKER_05]: And the House has an extension until April 7.

319
00:29:49,447 --> 00:30:04,338
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's one where folks are interested in supporting that one, that writing letters of support to the House would be a useful thing to do at this point.

320
00:30:12,030 --> 00:30:14,732
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that might be it for my updates.

321
00:30:14,872 --> 00:30:16,954
[SPEAKER_05]: Anybody have any questions on anything?

322
00:30:16,974 --> 00:30:32,266
[SPEAKER_11]: I didn't quite catch all of those dates regarding zoning, but if that's something that can be sent around or whatever, that would be great.

323
00:30:34,393 --> 00:30:40,840
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, and that's not for zoning, that's just for bills that are moving through the State House.

324
00:30:41,080 --> 00:30:44,604
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I can definitely send those around too.

325
00:30:46,644 --> 00:30:56,529
[SPEAKER_07]: And I just want to make a suggestion that in addition to you know writing to the one's representatives to encourage him to support those bills.

326
00:30:57,829 --> 00:31:13,377
[SPEAKER_07]: It's also a good idea to write us thank you to those senators to where the and with the word for it to who supported the bill before it was passed let them know we appreciate that.

327
00:31:17,412 --> 00:31:18,073
[SPEAKER_05]: that's a good point.

328
00:31:32,392 --> 00:31:34,515
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, I think that's it for my updates then.

329
00:31:37,490 --> 00:31:39,351
[SPEAKER_02]: Brenda, I have a question.

330
00:31:39,371 --> 00:31:44,493
[SPEAKER_02]: Maybe this is an appropriate place to ask it.

331
00:31:45,013 --> 00:31:56,379
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there any action on cleaning up the alewife brook where it flows into the mystic in Medford?

332
00:31:56,479 --> 00:32:03,022
[SPEAKER_02]: I know that there was some renewed interest in eliminating the CSOs and SSOs.

333
00:32:04,083 --> 00:32:07,849
[SPEAKER_02]: in the area, but I don't know if there's anything that the city's involved in.

334
00:32:10,412 --> 00:32:14,939
[SPEAKER_05]: There's nothing that I'm involved in, but that doesn't mean that the city isn't involved in it.

335
00:32:14,999 --> 00:32:17,823
[SPEAKER_05]: So I can follow up and get back to you about it.

336
00:32:18,524 --> 00:32:18,865
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

337
00:32:37,588 --> 00:32:40,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Shall we move on to the Trees Medford updates?

